  <h1>Sterling-Pro Commercial Dishwasher Repair — Los Angeles &amp; Southern California</h1>

  <p>Sterling-Pro is a British commercial catering equipment brand — they've been supplying the independent UK catering equipment market since 2009, manufacturing glasswashers, undercounter dishwashers, and passthrough machines that are European-manufactured and positioned as reliable mid-tier warewashing for pubs, cafés, restaurants, and small hospitality operations. In the LA market, Sterling-Pro equipment shows up in British-managed hospitality contexts — the same segment where you'd find Classeq glasswashers and Washtech undercounters — and occasionally in second-hand commercial kitchen purchases where the original provenance isn't clearly documented.</p>

  <p>Sterling-Pro is not a brand that most US commercial appliance companies know. Their parts distribution is through UK channels — Parts Town UK carries their spares, not the US Parts Town network. When LA operators with Sterling-Pro equipment call for service, they typically run into the same wall as with Classeq and Washtech: either "we don't service that brand" or a technician who arrives without the right knowledge. We service Sterling-Pro throughout SoCal. $120 commercial diagnostic applied to the repair. Call <strong>{phone}</strong>.</p>

  <h2>Sterling-Pro Equipment We Service</h2>

  <h3>SPG Series — Glasswashers</h3>
  <p>The Sterling-Pro SPG series glasswashers — SPG400, SPG500, SPG600, SPG700, SPG800 — are their compact undercounter glasswashers for bar and café service. The numbers indicate approximate glasses-per-hour capacity. These are high-temperature machines using a booster element for the final sanitizing rinse, without chemical sanitizer. In LA's hard water, the booster element is the primary maintenance concern — same pattern as every other high-temp glasswasher in this market. Monthly descaling is appropriate. The SPG series door interlock switch is a wear item in high-cycle bar environments; when it fails, the machine won't initiate a cycle. We check the door switch first on any SPG call where the presenting complaint is total failure to start.</p>
  <p><strong>Models:</strong> SPG400, SPG500, SPG600, SPG700, SPG800</p>

  <h3>SP Series — Undercounter Dishwashers</h3>
  <p>The Sterling-Pro SP series undercounters cover small restaurant and café dishwashing in the same compact footprint as the glasswasher series. These are standard undercounter high-temp machines — booster heater, door-type loading, single-rack cycling. Service approach is the same as for any compact high-temp undercounter: booster element scale is the primary LA market maintenance issue, door switch is the primary wear failure, spray arm nozzle blockage from mineral deposits is the secondary maintenance concern.</p>
  <p><strong>Models:</strong> SP500, SP1000, SP2000, SP3000, SP4000, SP5000, SP6000, SP7000, SP8000, SP9000</p>

  <h3>SPH Series — Passthrough Dishwashers</h3>
  <p>The Sterling-Pro SPH series passthrough (hood-type) machines — SPH100, SPH200, SPH400, SPH500 — are their mid-volume restaurant machines. These are for operations that have outgrown an undercounter but don't need a full conveyor line. The SPH series uses the same European warewashing engineering as the glasswasher and undercounter lines — booster heater, high-temperature sanitization, straightforward electro-mechanical controls on earlier models and touch panel controls on current production. Service follows standard passthrough dishwasher protocol: booster element descaling, door seal inspection, spray arm maintenance.</p>
  <p><strong>Models:</strong> SPH100, SPH200, SPH400, SPH500</p>

  <h2>Parts Sourcing — The Reality for LA Operators</h2>

  <p>Sterling-Pro's parts distribution is primarily through the UK catering equipment market — Parts Town UK, AS Catering Supplies, and similar UK trade suppliers carry their spares. This is not connected to the US Parts Town network that most American commercial appliance companies use. When other LA service companies decline Sterling-Pro calls citing parts availability, that's often the specific reason: they've checked US parts channels, found nothing, and stopped there.</p>

  <p>We source Sterling-Pro parts through UK trade channels and Moffat/Waldorf Group distribution for equivalent European platform components. Common wear items for the SPG and SP series — booster elements, door switch assemblies, spray arm components, door gaskets — have lead times of 5–7 business days from UK sources. For SPH passthrough machines, 7–10 business days on most components. We'll give you an honest parts timeline on-site. For the majority of Sterling-Pro failures in the LA market, the fault is a standard wear component: scaled booster element, worn door switch, or blocked spray nozzles. These are serviceable once the part arrives, and in the interim we can often restore partial function while waiting on parts.</p>

  <h2>Recent Sterling-Pro Service Calls</h2>

  <h3>"SPG500 glasswasher — won't start, British-managed café Santa Monica"</h3>
  <p>Café called — Sterling-Pro SPG500 glasswasher completely inoperative, no power to the cycle. Owner had a stack of service records from the UK, confirmed it was original equipment from when the café concept opened. Door interlock switch had failed — no continuity through the door safety circuit even with the door fully closed. Sourced the switch through UK trade channel, 6 business day lead time. Ran the café without the glasswasher for one service week while waiting for the part, installed on arrival, verified operation through ten cycles. Set the owner on a monthly descaling schedule using a UK-compatible deliming agent available from restaurant supply on Pico.</p>

  <h3>"SPH200 passthrough — temperature not reaching sanitization, restaurant West Hollywood"</h3>
  <p>British restaurant concept on Santa Monica Blvd, SPH200 passthrough running cycles but dishes coming out wet and with residue — classic booster element scale pattern. Temperature probe was reading correctly but heat transfer from the element to the water was compromised by calcium carbonate insulation on the element surface. Full descale with citric acid solution, post-descale temperature verification confirmed 180°F final rinse. Set the restaurant on quarterly descaling. They'd been maintaining the machine on a UK annual descaling schedule, which doesn't account for LA's water hardness.</p>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <p><strong>Why is Sterling-Pro so hard to find service for in Los Angeles?</strong><br>
  Sterling-Pro is a UK commercial catering brand with parts distribution through British trade channels. Their equipment is not in the US commercial service training ecosystem, and their parts aren't in US distribution networks. We service Sterling-Pro throughout SoCal by sourcing through UK channels — call {phone} and describe your model, and we'll confirm service availability and parts lead times before dispatching.</p>

  <p><strong>How long do Sterling-Pro parts take to source in Los Angeles?</strong><br>
  Common wear parts (booster elements, door switches, spray arm components, gaskets) are 5–7 business days from UK trade sources. SPH passthrough components typically 7–10 business days. We'll confirm the specific part availability at the diagnostic visit and give you an honest timeline. In most cases we can identify and diagnose the fault on the first visit and have the repair completed when the part arrives.</p>

  <p><strong>How often should Sterling-Pro equipment be descaled in Los Angeles?</strong><br>
  Monthly for glasswashers and undercounters; quarterly for SPH passthrough booster elements. UK maintenance schedules assume softer water than LA's 250–350 ppm TDS. If your maintenance schedule came with the machine from the UK, it needs to be recalibrated for LA conditions.</p>

  <p><strong>What is your diagnostic fee?</strong><br>
  $120 commercial diagnostic, applied to the repair when you proceed. On-site quote — what we quote is what's on the invoice.</p>

